<article id="post-611" class="post-611 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-general category-pop-culture">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2007/01/rankin-family-reunion-in-calgary/" rel="bookmark">Rankin Family Reunion in Calgary</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>Last night, we attended what I can only describe as a typical Maritime house/kitchen party. Except without the screech or incomprehensible accents.<br />
Back in the early 1990s, Canada had a brief flirtation with popular Maritime music. While the Maritimes loved the music to begin with, the rest of us uncultured folk had to wait for the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_content">CanCon rules</a> to bring it into the public eye.<br />
Along with <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leahy">Leahy</a> (who hit the big scene a couple of years earlier) and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Big_Sea">Great Big Sea</a> (who rolled in with the tide a couple of years later), <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Rankins">The Rankin Family</a> made up a significant portion of the Maritime component of the Canadian airwaves.<br />
I&#8217;d heard one or two of their tunes before. Nice, but I didn&#8217;t go out of my way to buy an album.<br />
 <a href="http://geoff.wp/2007/01/rankin-family-reunion-in-calgary/#more-611" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> &#8220;Rankin Family Reunion in Calgary&#8221;</span></a></p>
	</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	<footer class="entry-footer">
		<span class="byline"><span class="author vcard"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/095609f98b14811f33ecac14add504b3?s=49&#038;d=mm&#038;r=r' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/095609f98b14811f33ecac14add504b3?s=98&#038;d=mm&#038;r=r 2x' class='avatar avatar-49 photo' height='49' width='49' loading='lazy'/><span class="screen-reader-text">Author </span> <a class="url fn n" href="http://geoff.wp/author/sonworf/">Geoff</a></span></span><span class="posted-on"><span class="screen-reader-text">Posted on </span><a href="http://geoff.wp/2007/01/rankin-family-reunion-in-calgary/" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published updated" datetime="2007-01-24T20:48:07-07:00">24 January 2007</time></a></span><span class="cat-links"><span class="screen-reader-text">Categories </span><a href="http://geoff.wp/category/general/" rel="category tag">General</a>, <a href="http://geoff.wp/category/pop-culture/" rel="category tag">Pop Culture</a></span><span class="comments-link"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2007/01/rankin-family-reunion-in-calgary/#comments">2 Comments<span class="screen-reader-text"> on Rankin Family Reunion in Calgary</span></a></span>			</footer><!-- .entry-footer -->
</article><!-- #post-611 -->

<article id="post-610" class="post-610 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-general category-pop-culture category-rants tag-palaces">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2007/01/forbidden-starbucks/" rel="bookmark">Forbidden Starbucks</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>I came across an article in Yahoo!&#8217;s <a href="http://news.yahoo.com/i/757">Oddly Enough</a> section this morning about how an internet protest movement is <a href="http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20070118/od_nm/china_starbucks_forbidden_city_dc">might drive out Starbucks from their location in the Forbidden City</a>.<br />
Frankly, I&#8217;m trying to understand how the Chinese government let it in there in the first place.<br />
 <a href="http://geoff.wp/2007/01/forbidden-starbucks/#more-610" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> &#8220;Forbidden Starbucks&#8221;</span></a></p>
	</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	<footer class="entry-footer">
